{{For|similarly titled battles|Siege of Athens (disambiguation){{!}}Siege of Athens}} {{Infobox military conflict |conflict=Siege of Athens |image= |caption= |partof= |date=287 BC |place=[[Athens]] |result= Athenian victory |combatant1=[[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedonia]] |combatant2=[[Athens]] |commander1=[[Demetrius I of Macedon]] |commander2=Olympiodorus |strength1= |strength2= |casualties1= |casualties2= |}}
The '''Siege of Athens''' lasted through 287 BC when the city was put under siege by King [[Demetrius I of Macedon]]. Athens revolted in that year against Demetrius' rule and elected Olympiodorus as [[strategos]]. Olympiodorus raised a force among the Athenian citizens, including old men and children, and attacked the Macedonian garrison that had retreated to the fort at the Museum hill which he took with the loss of just 13 of his men.<ref name="Hammond230">Hammond ; Walbank 1988, p. 230</ref>
On receiving news of the revolt Demetrius gathered forces from the cities he still held and put Athens under siege.<ref name="Hammond231">Hammond ; Walbank 1988, p. 231</ref> The Athenians sent the philosopher [[Crates of Athens|Crates]] to negotiate with Demetrius.<ref name="Hammond231"/> In the treaty signed Demetrius received some fortresses in [[Attica]] but Athens was freed from a Macedonian garrison.<ref name="Hammond231"/>
